# Prototyping

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Prototyping is a skill and tool used in public and social innovation to develop and test ideas, products, or services at an early stage before large-scale implementation.

## Purpose
The purpose of prototyping is to explore multiple solutions to a problem, test their viability, and gather user feedback to refine and improve the idea.

## How it works
Prototyping involves creating a physical or digital model of a product or service, testing it with users, gathering feedback, and iterating on the design based on that feedback. This process can be repeated multiple times until the desired outcome is achieved.

## Requirements
To effectively use prototyping for R&D, clear objectives, a cross-disciplinary team, an iterative process, resource allocation, and evaluation metrics are necessary.

## Reflections
Prototyping is a valuable approach to innovation in the public sector, allowing for experimentation, learning, and adaptation. Embracing a culture of experimentation and learning is essential for mainstreaming prototyping within service development processes.

## Related methods (if any)
Prototyping is often used in conjunction with other methods such as experimentation, Minimal Viable Product (MVP), and design thinking.

## Examples
Examples of prototyping in action include the development of solar mobile kiosks for street youths and women running small businesses, as showcased by the UNDP Cameroon Accelerator Lab team.
